description: From Middle English leden, leaden, from Old English lēaden (“leaden, of lead”), equivalent to lead +‎ -en. Cognate with West Frisian leaden (“leaden”), Dutch loden (“leaden”).

adjectives.description: leaden (comparative more leaden, superlative most leaden)

entries.meaning: Pertaining to or resembling lead; grey, heavy, sluggish.
examples: [...] if man beThe passive thing you say, I should not seeMuch harm in the religions and old saws(Tho' I may never own such leaden laws)Which break a teachless nature to the yoke.
the sky was leaden and thick

verbs.description: leaden (third-person singular simple present leadens, present participle leadening, simple past and past participle leadened)

entries.meaning: (transitive, intransitive) To make or become dull or overcast.
